Here's a quickie, explicit definition of each:<br>
<br>
mode: the value of the abscissa corresponding to the maximum ordinate of a *frequency* distribution curve.  Has no explicit relationship to mean/average/median values.<br>
<br>
arithmetic mean, syn. average: (a1 + a2 + ... aN)/N (for a noncontinuous function)<br>
<br>
median: central term in a sequence of values arranged in order of magnitude.<br>
<br>
In plain english, the mode is the &quot;most common&quot; value in a dataset, the mean is the total sum value of the data divided by the number of datapoints, and the median is the data point with an equal number of points greater and less than it.<br>
<br>
They aren't even nearly equal or equivalent when looking at EQ damage output datasets.  I explicitly used mode because I was talking about frequency not magnitude.  The REASON I was discussing frequency because the EQ damage datasets I've seen are NOT smooth, continuous functions, they are bimodal/trimodal, and the modes tend to drive the mean quite strongly.<br>
